// NOTE: Integrated into the Fusion FSN tree for migration traceability.
// CONTENT:
// Product Guide: Fusion Core (nucleus)Component ID: F-CORE-001Classification: Foundational LayerAuthor: Lead Architect1. Vision & PurposeStandard Rust's std library is a masterpiece of general-purpose engineering, designed to interface seamlessly with everything from Windows to Linux to macOS. However, Fusion Core (codenamed nucleus) is engineered for a different reality: absolute, cycle-perfect determinism.It provides the minimal set of primitives required to build high-performance, panic-free systems without relying on an underlying operating system's memory manager or unpredictable system calls. While std optimizes for throughput in noisy environments, Fusion Core optimizes for latency and predictability in isolated execution contexts (like WebAssembly, Unikernels, or Embedded Metal). It serves as the bedrock for the "Unified Monolith" architecture, ensuring that the lowest layer of the stack is completely transparent to the compiler.2. Technical Replacement SpecsFusion Core does not wrap the standard library; it replaces it. By removing the dependency on libc, we gain complete control over the runtime behavior.ReplacesStandard Rust EquivalentFusion ImplementationTechnical RationaleAllocatorstd::alloc::GlobalAllocfusion::mem::ArenaDeterministic Latency. Standard allocators (malloc/jemalloc) have unpredictable execution times due to fragmentation handling and lock contention. The Arena uses bump-pointer allocation (O(1)) with zero locking.Smart PointersBox<T>, Arc<T>Ref<T>, StaticRef<T>Pointer Compression. Ref<T> uses relative addressing (offsets) rather than absolute 64-bit pointers. This allows us to store more pointers in the L1 cache and enables the entire memory heap to be serialized to disk and reloaded at a different address without pointer swizzling.CollectionsVec<T>, HashMap<K, V>FVec<T>, FMap<K, V>Stack-First Design. FVec defaults to inline storage (Small Vector Optimization) significantly larger than standard implementations, avoiding heap interaction for 90% of temporary collections.Error HandlingResult<T, E> (unrestricted)Checked<T, E> (strictly stack-local)Allocation-Free Errors. Fusion errors are strictly Copy types. They cannot allocate memory to store a stack trace string. This forces error handling to be lightweight and prevents "out of memory" handlers from causing another out of memory error.3. Core Functions & Signaturesfusion::mem::ArenaA region-based allocator that eliminates fragmentation and provides cache locality by default./// Allocates a value within the specified memory region.
// /// 
// /// Unlike `Box::new()`, this operation cannot fail due to fragmentation 
// /// and does not involve a syscall. It strictly increments a pointer.
// pub fn allocate_in<T>(arena: &Arena, value: T) -> Ref<T>
// // Note: Ref<T> is a non-null, alignment-aware relative pointer.
// // It tracks lifetimes via the Arena's internal generation ID, preventing 
// // use-after-free errors even in unsafe blocks.
// fusion::text::FStrA Small-String Optimized (SSO) string type designed for high-throughput text processing, such as parsing JSON or HTTP headers./// Creates an immutable string reference.
// ///
// /// If the string is < 23 bytes (on 64-bit systems), it is stored entirely 
// /// within the struct, avoiding a pointer indirection.
// pub const fn from_static(s: &'static str) -> FStr
// // 23 bytes stored inline; 0 heap allocation for most identifiers, keys, and names.
// // This significantly reduces cache misses during heavy string comparison loops.
// fusion::mem::FMapA hash map designed for the arena allocator./// A cache-friendly Open Addressing hash map.
// ///
// /// It does not use linked lists (chaining) for collisions, which destroys 
// /// cache locality. Instead, it uses Robin Hood hashing to keep elements 
// /// tightly packed in memory.
// pub struct FMap<K, V> {
//     entries: Ref<[Entry<K, V>]>,
//     load_factor: u8,
// }
// 4. Why this existsIn mission-critical infrastructure, latency spikes are indistinguishable from failure. We cannot tolerate the unpredictable latency of malloc seeking a free block during a high-frequency trading tick, or the binary bloat of the full std library when deploying thousands of micro-lambdas.Binary Size: Fusion Core allows us to compile the entire ecosystem into a sub-1MB binary if stripped, making cold starts near-instantaneous.Snapshotting: Because Ref<T> uses relative addressing, we can take a memcpy snapshot of the application's RAM, save it to disk, and restore it later. This enables "instant resume" functionality that is impossible with standard absolute pointers.Auditability: With a custom core, there is no "black box" code inside the OS allocator. Every byte of memory usage is accounted for within the Arena structs, allowing for perfect memory telemetry without overhead.
